segments.text: Testing, testing, one, two, one, two, one, two, three, four.
Hello, hello, testing, one, two, three, four.
Ray's got a little headache with this sexual orientation, doesn't he?
This is August 23rd in the Harrington building, and I have the honor and pleasure of interviewing Professor John Hoyle about his three decades or more service here at A&M.
John, to begin with, to introduce yourself to some stranger who might listen to this tape or read the transcript, describe your background before you came to A&M.
Where did you grow up?
What did Mom and Dad do?
Where did you go to college?
Where were you working before A&M?
Okay.
Well, I was born in a small town in Oklahoma, Rush Springs, Oklahoma, February 2, 1935, born in the house.
The house is still there, still stands in a little town.
And...
We moved around quite a lot as a child because dad trying to find employment and those kinds of things.
But I wound up in high school, my final two years in high school at Tulsa Will Rogers High School.
My older sister, Beverly, was two years ahead of me.
She finished at Tulsa Central High School and my younger brother, Jay, who's two years younger, finished
at Longview High School.
They moved again after I graduated from high school at Tulsa Will Rogers.
And then I made the decision to come to Texas A&M.
One of my classmates' dad, Ted Wrench, his daughter Dorothy was a high school classmate of mine.
And Ted had seen me play baseball for Tulsa Will Rogers and knew Bo Bell, the head baseball coach at Texas A&M.
And I got in touch with him, and they offered me a scholarship.
And the former student association, Tulsa, Oklahoma, paid my out-of-state tuition.
And we came here then.
I was a freshman here in the fall of 1953.
Lived in the athletic dorm, which was in Hart Hall.
And all the athletes were in Hart Hall, in football, basketball, track, swimming, all of us, which made it rather interesting.
That was before Bear Bryant came and set up a new athletic dorm, Henderson Hall, for football.
We were all together there in this hot, forsaken place.
I'll never forget, we drove down all night from Tulsa.
We got into College Station about 3 in the morning.
There was no motel rooms.
They were all taken.
About close to 7,000 students that year, and the Corps was mandatory, which I did not know when I got here.
I didn't know there were no women here.
I had no idea.
I had a baseball scholarship.
And folks had driven all night.
No place to stay.
We'd drive back to Hearn and get a, it was a big kind of a boarding house type thing.
And we spent two or three hours sleeping.
And then I came on campus the next morning and met Coach Bell.
And part of my job was to be a Sevesa volunteer, to wait tables in Sevesa.
And I remember I was playing in a baseball championship in Kansas, a Jayhawk League or a Van Johnson League, and made a mistake going into a barbershop and saying, take off my sideburns.
Well, he gave me a burr haircut and skinned the side of my head to a white wall.
And I got to College Station, and I was a hero among the upperclassmen.
So we started in a corps in A athletics.
And that was my early orientation.
Jim Cashin, a local here, had played football for the Aggies in the 40s.
And his brother, Red Cashin, of course, a famous football official.
He was our dorm advisor.
He was the one to keep all the athletes in some kind of order
And he told me the story later.
Mother and Dad had driven me all the way down here in an old Nash automobile.
And they're getting ready to leave, and Mother turns over to this very proud Captain Cashin and said, please take care of my little boy.
And Cashin's laughed about that over the years because he had to watch me as hard as any of the rest of them that first year with some of the crazy antics that we did.
But that was sort of an early orientation of where we came from.
where I came from.
Okay, then after you graduated, when?
I graduated in 1957.
And then where?
Went to Odessa, Texas.
At that time, I was even thinking about being a pro baseball player.
I didn't take a contract with a corps because I was really interested in trying to play some professional baseball.
And I had married, and Carolyn was going to finish that summer at TCU.
And so I just decided to forego the baseball, pro baseball, and took a teaching and coaching position.
And I taught math and science and coached junior high sports.
And Carolyn taught English in Odessa.
And we had our first child there, Johnny, who's now a counselor here in the local junior high school in College Station.
And then the military called.
Rather than going in for three years, I went in for six months.
And I was classified as critical skill at that time, Haskell, because Slick Rutherford was our area representative.
They called him Slick Rutherford.
And the US government then knew we had to catch the Russians in space.
And I was a science teacher.
And I came back to school through the National Science Foundation to Texas A&M to learn science.
I took courses in physics and so on in order to teach students and get ready to catch the Russians in space, which we did.
My small part probably was not very significant, but we did catch the Russians in space.
My mother had been a constant encourager throughout that.
She had three years of college at Oklahoma College for Women in Chickasha.
She had her teaching certificate, never taught a day.
My dad was a 10th grade dropout.
He was a salesman, wound up with the home state farm insurance and later American General.
He retired at age 62, and he's 91 now and still living.
Mother died two years ago, but
Mother was the one who really encouraged me intellectually, academically, got me interested in music, and that, she's been gone two years, but she was very much an influence there.
All right, so you taught, this is in the Odessa system.
Odessa, Ector County, Ector County School District.
I was there four years.
And then where?
Went to Ector, I mean, went to Midland High School.
I had wanted to be head baseball coach,
And about that time, I had finished up my master's degree through the National Science Foundation and got my certification for school administration.
Where?
Here at Texas A&M through Dr. Paul Hensling, who was such an influential person in my life.
Some of those individuals in education, Walter was in psychology.
Barbel?
Walter Barbel.
Barbel was on my committee.
And then I was named head baseball coach at Midland High School.
which is one of my dreams.
I wanted to coach, be the head coach of a high school baseball team.
And finished my master's then about after two years.
And the superintendent out there called me in and says, John, Dr. Hensling at Texas A&M tells me you're ready for school administration.
Your coaching days are over.
And I was doing pretty well, but I knew that that was a career I wanted to go.
And then I got really excited.
Dr. Hensling says, you need to go get a PhD.
I knew I was a pretty good student.
as an undergraduate.
When I really wanted to study, I could.
I could make it.

But being an athlete and looking at pro ball and looking at, you know, where the women were because there weren't any here and those kinds of things, I wasn't focused as clearly as I should have been.
But he and others said, John, you're a good student.
Go to Colorado University.
I've done a master's study for Dr. Paul Hensling.
It was a three-hour problems course on Ph.D. and Ed.D.
nationwide.
I did that study for Dr. Hensling.
He then put together the proposal for the Ph.D. program here for Texas A&M University.
And you were involved in that.
You were here as dean of faculties and so on when I was a doctoral student.
And I remember you grading the proposals for the dissertations.
And I remember your little, I'll never forget this, don't use one-sentence paragraphs.
You said that.
And I never have since that time.
I struggled through three years there.
I was able to transfer work from Colorado University.
I started up there, had two semesters, and A&M's program was approved in 1964 by the coordinating board.
Dr. Hensling put it together with the support of President Rutter and certainly our dean, Frank Hubert.
But he really was the hammer for getting that Ph.D. program together.
So you got your doctoral degree here?
I got it here.
I transferred my work in 1967.
I transferred and worked in Colorado University and they accepted it in 67.
PhD, at that point, I really enjoyed my research.
My research was in the behavioral science area and applying it to schools and leadership.
And I had a chance then to become assistant superintendent at Harlingen, making quite a bit of money, or go to TCU as a beginning professor for half the salary.
Well, I was teaching, thanks to Dr. Hensling, teaching undergraduate students in educational psychology and social foundations.
And I really loved it.
I felt like that's where I belong.
So TCU is where we went in 67, January of 67.
Stayed there three years.
What was that TCU salary?
TCU salary was $12,500 for 10 12 months.
And the assistant superintendency was $22,500.
And that was big money.
But I knew there was something there.
And first year, in fact, Rotary International selected me for some reason as one of five outstanding young Texans from the Dallas-Fort Worth, Texas area.
And I went to New Zealand with five other people for four months and really started getting interested in international kinds of things.
Stayed at TCU two years, and then I had a postdoc in computer-assisted learning at TCU.
under the great Dr. Herbert Legron, who was the dean of education at TCU, brilliant man.
And then West Texas State at the time was trying to start a computer-assisted large group, small group educational psychology program.
And I went out there for a year.
And from there, I went to Miami of Ohio, where
The dean there, Dean Bogner, and a guy named Charles Techman, said we want you to write and publish and learn.
We want you to really become a significant scholar, and we'll protect you from a lot of the things that young professors have to put up with.
Stayed there four years.
Came back then to Tulsa University in 1974 as department head, thinking I'd be there forever.
Hometown.
Mother and dad lived there.
Sister and brother-in-law lived there.
And all of a sudden, I met a bunch of Texas A&M faculty at a national meeting, and I'd just been named a good fortune.
Larry Haskew, through his influence at the University of Texas, he and some others elected me president of the National Council of Professors of Administration.
And I was really 40, I guess 39, 40 years old.
The next thing I know, Dr. Hawkins here, Harold Hawkins, Frank Hubert,

were calling me and offering me a chance to come and interview for an open position here in educational administration, especially in some of the research, organizational theory, and futures visioning kind of thing.
Well, I came here after only one year at Tulsa and thinking, well, that's a quick move.
And I was afraid that some of the old professors remembered me as being not too smart or not being too brilliant or something.
But they had all either retired or died or something else.
And so we thought it all over, and here I wound up coming here in the fall of 75.
Describe the interview process.
All right.
First thing, when I came in, it was a matter of talking with Dr. Hawkins about the program.
Of course, Dr. Hensling was here, was pushing me without any question.
He thought I could do no wrong because that's how I felt about him.
And he was pushing me and some of the younger colleagues my age were pushing me who had seen me at the national level.
Jim McNamara, for instance, recommended me because of some of my research.
And I met with some of the faculty, and then here I go up to Frank Hubert.
He and Hawkins were together.
Well, I'd worked for Frank Hubert as his assistant dean, not officially, but assistant graduate student dean.
And he was a little bit intimidating.
And I never knew exactly when I was around him
you know, whether to laugh or be serious.
He was on my doctoral committee as well.
Tough.
Do you remember any key questions he asked?
Oh, yeah, yeah.
He asked me about my line of research and wanted to know how I could make that research relevant to improving schools, those kinds of things.
And then he
He said, here are the courses you'll be teaching, and you've got a tough act to follow with McNamara.
I said, I understand that.
McNamara went off to Columbia for a year and then came back.
And some of those kinds of questions, I didn't have to make a formal presentation at the time.
And then I said, well, here's what my salary, here's what I need.
And I said something to the effect that...
That this is what it'll take.
And I'm up for full professor at Tulsa University.
I want to be considered for that when I come here at the end of one year.

Well, I didn't get full professor, but I got tenure at the end of one year because at that time we had a new vice president come in here who said there'll be no Aggies promoted, you know, while I'm here.
This is 70.
That was 1975, fall of 75.
We had a provost and vice president.
Kind of trying to think of his name.
He was in medicine.
He was in...
Wait, 75?
Yeah, 75.
Calhoun was vice president in 75.
No, no.
A brand new one.
They just put in a brand new one.
I think he was on the State Board of Education later.
I can't think of his name.
And you're not thinking about Winerdi?
No, no, when Ernie was assistant or associate to him at the time.
And it's 75.
Because see, Williams is president from 70 to 76.
And Calhoun is serving under him until 77.
Yeah, but there was somebody else that came in in 76.
I can't think of his name.
He was sort of a short guy in medicine.
It was at Radar on State Road anyway.
And they said, well, he said, we've recommended you across the street, but they're not promoting any ag.
I said, well, didn't you tell them I'd been gone and been away?
Well, it was that kind of thing.
And that was the only time I was really upset being here.
But I went ahead and I received tenure.
And I won't ask Sally anymore.
What was the beginning salary here?
Twenty, twenty-five, twenty-five.
which represented about a $4,000 raise from Tulsa University.
Did you get the impression that they were, were you one of a bunch that they were considering, or did you have the impression they were trying to attract you?
There was not a bunch.
McNamara, who had already developed a pretty good national reputation, he and I were doing some similar kind of research.
And he told Frank Hubert, here's the guy.
And Frank had such respect for Jim.
It was pretty much a done deal if I could get enough salary to make it worthwhile and to make the move because we had a good situation in Tulsa.
Describe moving your family and settling in Bryan College Station at that time.
Okay.
We, of course, it was one of those last, we didn't know until probably July we were coming.
So we started looking for a place to stay.
We found a house down on Pershing, five bedroom, nice big house that belonged to an individual in biology who was in Australia on sabbatical.
We leased that house.
Wanted to buy it, but he wouldn't sell it.
And so we built then down Southwood Valley.
But I remember how hot it was.
Homer Adams moved us in here.
And I had known him as when I was an undergraduate.
And I just remember how hot it was, how miserable it was.
But the house was air conditioned.
It had a nice shade and all those kinds of things.
I couldn't get any kids in school.
See, I had a son who was already, he'd been a sophomore at Tulsa Memorial, trying to bring him in as a sophomore.
He wasn't too pleased with that, but it's a lot smaller high school, and he was a pretty little basketball player, and I was hoping he would adjust.
And he did.
My daughter, though, however, she comes into the schools,
Didn't have any friends.
And it was difficult for her until probably her junior year in high school.
And she doesn't look back on high school with as much fun.
Sometimes it really affects one child more than it does the other, as you well know.
I don't regret it, but I wish she had had a happier junior high and high school experience.
And I've often thought, well, maybe I wasn't too sensitive about that.
But anyway.
They both graduated from Texas A&M, and Laura's teaching down in Friendswood.
Her husband, Ross, is an Aggie in engineering.
He's with Hewlett Packard, 14 and 10-year-old grandsons.
Son John is here, a counselor at the junior high, seventh grade, has a master's degree, a bachelor's here, a master's from SFA in counseling.
His wife, Julie, teaches at Sam Rayburn in Bryan, two grandkids.
Winston is 11, no, 10, playing football, 11.
playing football here at the seventh grade junior high.
I'm going to go out and watch him at four o'clock today.
And then Jennifer started first grade this year.
So we've got four Aggies really.
If I could interview your wife about the move, what do you think she would say about moving down here then?
Oh, it was home.
Her mother and father were still living.
And so it was home because when we came back to graduate school here,
her mom helped us find a rent house.
They were good babysitters and not only that,
I think during that period of time, I never had to worry about having a car problem because my father-in-law, Frenchie Falgo, worked at Hossle Garage and could fix anything.
And as long as it was his baby's car, she was an only.
So it was really, she was glad to came back because of her family ties here.
And she went to high school in Stephen F. Austin here in Bryan.
So she knew a lot of people.
She immediately got a job.
She had finished her master's at Miami of Ohio.

and had a strong English background, so they hired her at Blinn College, and she, for 15 years, has been assistant department head of English and just stepped out of that this year, and now she's teaching part-time, teaching two classes a week, but that was really good for her to come back.
I mean, it was frustrating, but we were still young enough and had a lot of young friends that we blended in with the church and
We've been a member of the Disciples of Christ Church, First Christian Church, ever since we married.
So we've been involved in that ever since we came here.
Describe the department as you arrived and becoming a part of that group.
All right.
It was interesting.
It had a split between the practitioner type, former superintendent type.
like Dr. Henseling, like Dr. Les Richardson.
And then we had a community ed program.
Bob Barrage and others had become kind of nationally well-known in community ed.
The scholarship and the publications, it was just beginning with two or three.
Phil West was very good.
He was on the staff in terms of scholarship.
But we then
After one year, we were able then to bring in Dr. David Erlandson.
And then Jim McNamara came back the third year.
So we began to develop a really good, solid scholarship and became more and more prominent across the nation.
And now, of course, we've hired minorities, women, and really have a fine, diverse faculty and consider ourselves in the top 10% around the country.
And I think we are.
at that time was there tension in the department between those two factions?
Not so much as there is now.

We needed more tension at the time because here I was trying to work with the practitioners because I'd known a bunch of them through my public school days and also trying to develop my scholarship agenda.
Here I was trying to do both and some weren't publishing anything
And it was awkward, really, for me to try to move into the academic arena when I could have gotten by pretty well without doing it.
But I'm glad I continued doing the writing and publishing.
And it's been good.
And now it's a real joy for me to be at the stage in my career where I'm asked to do articles for referee journals and chapters for books and books.
And I'm pleased to ask my younger colleagues.
I say, hey, I don't have time to do this.
Would you help me do this, co-author these things?
And that's a real joy to see that happen.
Prior to your coming, what was your most best known research product?
I think probably work I'd done in school climate and our dealing with school cultures.
I had done some research in some major cities.
going and actually spending time with schools to finding schools where there really was an open environment for learning as opposed to a very rigid, structured kind of learning.
I guess I developed that pretty well.
And then it was very soon after that when I was invited and I got what is known as the National Professor of the Year honor for American Association of School Administrators.
And in 82, I went to Washington for four months.

and wrote the first set of guidelines for the preparation of school administrators, which has evolved into the new ISLIC state national standards created by a group from the chief state school officers.
And then I chaired the national commission on standards for the superintendency.
So I've become known, I guess, by having a lot of support and a lot of help by this department, Texas A&M.
They've encouraged me.
Dr. Hawkins did.
David Erlandson did.
And now, of course, Brian Cole does.
They've never tried to get me too tied up with administration.
And I have had chances to become dean at other places.
But I said, well, I want a career where I can travel, I can write.
And now I've become very fortunate.
I've been invited to speak to a lot of national conferences, futures conferences.
I was lucky enough, fortunate enough, to keynote the first National Cooperative Extension Conference in Cincinnati two years ago on the future envisioning and things like that.
And I'm working now with the College of Business here on campus with their executive development programs.
And then, as you know, with FSIS, teaching courses in creative thinking, problem solving, and coaching kinds of things.
So I'm glad 15 years ago, 20 years ago,
when I decided I don't want to be a dean.

I'm glad I made that decision and stuck with it because a lot of my friends went dean, then professor, dean, back professor, and they never did become deans, but they never did move in the mainstream of their discipline either.
And so I've been lucky there maybe.
I don't know whether I've been a good dean.

I respect people who do become good deans, but those are the tough decisions that we have in faculty life because everybody thinks, oh, here's a guy who can speak well, likes people, he'd be a great dean.
Everybody pushes you to be a dean or be a vice president or something else.
And our discipline's had a hard time gaining respect anyway.
And so I've tried to be in that fight to say we have a knowledge base, we prepare leaders as well as anybody, and here's some of our proof and our research and those kinds of things.
So it's being proud of our discipline, I guess, and what we're trying to do has kept me in it.
And when you got here, who was the department chairman?
Dr. Hal Hawkins.
And should I say head or chairman?
Yeah, he was head.
Yeah.
Describe his administrative style.
Well, pretty much down the line, line of staff like the rest of the department heads were at that time in the 70s, like Frank Hubert was at the time.
There wasn't a lot of site-based decision-making.
I remember, I could remember, for instance...
kind of bucking the trend, we wanted to look at our knowledge, what we were teaching within the college and how it fit with the national thing.
And Dr. Hubert appointed me to a committee to write a concept paper, as he called it, on where we are in our discipline.
And I tried to explain all those things.
He was on the committee.
And I was still intimidated by him being on that committee, even though we were so-called equals.
And I'll never forget, he said, I found a professor.
I mean, a person who had been a former chancellor

either at the University of Missouri or some other institution, this was in the 77 or 8, I guess, that is retiring from, he may have been head of the Missouri State Coordinating Board or something of higher education.
So he wants to be a higher ed prof.
I said, excellent.
Does he have a degree in educational administration or in management?
Oh, no, it's in English or something.
And I'll never forget, I said, well, Dr. Hubert, that's kind of naive, isn't it?
You just had me write a concept paper about what we need to have in our discipline.
You're telling me you want to bring somebody in or teach higher ed?
And you know what?
People around the table thought I was going to be fired.
But he backed off and said, Hoyle's right.
He's got enough courage, enough conviction what his discipline's all about.
And I really respected him for that, because I thought he'd really be angry, because he wanted to bring in a buddy.
I think that was somebody that had once been in Austin while he was over there.
I think you're right.
I think you're right.
And then he went to Missouri.
I think it was the equivalent of the head of the coordinating board.
Because I think in Austin he had been the number two or number three man.
Yeah, that's right.
That's right.
So the department operated, by and large,
strong leadership.
Strong leadership, department head without question.
It wasn't any of this chair stuff where you rotate it.
And y'all were located where?
We were located in, we got, I was, we were in Harrington.
Already?
Yeah, we'd already moved two years before from academic building to Harrington.
And about how many were in the, on the faculty?
There were about seven, maybe eight.
We had probably an adjunct, but probably eight faculty.
And there were undergraduate and masters?
Well, at that point, you see, when I got back here, the College of Education had the Department of Educational Administration, all graduate programs.
The undergraduates were in EDCI, the Career Construction Teacher Education.
And it's the only time I've been able to work with undergraduates, even though I taught them at TCU in Miami, Ohio, as when Carolyn, my wife, and I take kids to Europe for the study abroad.
We've taken three groups of future teachers to Santa Chiara Study Center in Italy, where I teach undergraduate courses since I majored in education here at Texas A&M, not educational administration.
I had a minor in educational administration, but it really has helped me now, because I've taught Ed Psych, I've taught other courses,
because I had a good, broad, liberal education.

And I really think in many ways the early Ph.D. program here in education was stronger and more, I think, more comprehensive than our becoming too specialized in curriculum or in Ed Psych or in administration.
They made us go outside.
I took courses from Bard and Nelson.
in sociology, and I took social psychology.
I took philosophy under a new professor of philosophy we had here, and management under Dr. Rice.
I really, I wanted to, oh yeah, and a great course on great books from Dean John Paul Abbott.
And our students don't have that opportunity anymore.
Our programs are too tightly organized, and I've,
Most of the students I advise, I try to get them into philosophy, into the center, into the Bush Center, into business to expand them a little bit.
Did anyone give you advice as a new faculty member here?
What to do or not to do?
No, Dr. Hensling probably.
In sitting with him, just great wisdom that man had.
No, they just assumed I knew what I was supposed to do.
What were your first course assignments?
I picked up the course I'm teaching right now, The Nature and Problems of Administrative Behavior, which is
